            "public_access_description": "The Sleeping Beauty, designed for the Sadler's Wells (now Royal) Ballet in 1946, is Messel's most enduring production.  The fairy costumes and fantasy elements are set in a 'real' world, inspired by the soaring architectural fantasies of the 17th and 18th centuries and costumes based upon mid-late 17th century fashions, mixing English, Spanish and French period styles.\n\nThis costume for the Queen is in the Baroque manner, extravagant and encrusted with decoration which, in the drawing, seems almost alive.  In 1946, when there were severe restrictions on the supply of fabrics, finding enough lavish fabrics must have been very hard and, in the end, this dress was the most expensive in the whole production, costing over \u00a3100 - a huge sum in those days.  \n\nIn reality, the cloak and train, being of fur, would have been very heavy.  To produce something of the same weight on stage would not have been practical for the wearer, so they were made in net trimmed with 'ermine tails' and, around the edge, a tubular trim, which would have given it weight and shape in movement.  \n \nOliver Messel (1904-1978) was Britain\u2019s leading theatre designer throughout the 1930s, \u201840s and \u201850s, mastering every aspect of entertainment - ballet, drama, film, musical, opera and revue - as well working in interior decoration and textile design. His lavish, painterly and romantic concepts were perfectly in tune with the times and earned him an international reputation.  By 1960, however, that style was becoming unfashionable, and Messel gradually abandoned theatre and built a new career designing luxury homes in the Caribbean.", 
